  "articleSummary": "The article argues that multiple-choice questions, often dismissed as low-effort assessment tools, become powerful teaching instruments when wrong answers (distractors) are carefully designed to represent real misconceptions. Using a PostgreSQL identity column question as an example, the author shows how each distractor reveals a specific mental model (e.g., legacy syntax, SQL Server muscle memory), allowing the quiz to diagnose and teach across beginner, intermediate, and advanced levels. The tone is reflective and instructional, framed by the recurring metaphor that \"the distractor is the curriculum\" and that writing strong wrong answers forces instructional honesty. The intended audience includes technical writers, educators, and developers who create programming quizzes or tutorials.",
